%I A123693 #35 Jun 27 2026 10:38:56
%S A123693 5,491531
%N A123693 Primes p such that p^2 divides 7^(p-1) - 1.
%C A123693 No further terms below 1.2*10^15 (see Fischer link).
%C A123693 From _Chai Wah Wu_, Jun 26 2026: (Start)
%C A123693 Primes p such that binomial(7*p^2,p^2) == 7^p mod p^2.
%C A123693 More generally, if p>1 and p^2 divides q^(p-1)-1, then p does not divide q. Furthermore,
%C A123693 Theorem: Let p be prime and q be coprime to p. Then p^2 divides q^(p-1)-1 if and only if binomial(qp^2,p^2) == q^p mod p^2.
%C A123693 Proof: By generalized Lucas' theorem modulo p^2 (Rowland, 2022), binomial(qp^2,p^2) == binomial(q,1) mod p^2 == q mod p^2. Since gcd(q,p^2)=1, this implies that q is invertible mod p^2, implying that q^p == q mod p^2 if and only if q^(p-1) == 1 mod p^2, and the proof is complete. (End)
%H A123693 Amir Akbary and Sahar Siavashi, <a href="http://math.colgate.edu/~integers/s3/s3.Abstract.html">The Largest Known Wieferich Numbers</a>, INTEGERS, 18(2018), A3. See Table 1, p. 5.
%H A123693 F. G. Dorais and D. Klyve, <a href="https://cs.uwaterloo.ca/journals/JIS/VOL14/Klyve/klyve3.html">A Wieferich prime search up to p < 6.7*10^15</a>, J. Integer Seq. 14 (2011), Art. 11.9.2, 1-14.
%H A123693 R. Fischer, <a href="http://www.fermatquotient.com/FermatQuotienten/">Fermat quotients B^(P-1) == 1 (mod P^2)</a>.
%H A123693 W. Keller and J. Richstein, <a href="http://www1.uni-hamburg.de/RRZ/W.Keller/FermatQuotient.html">Fermat quotients q_p(a) that are divisible by p</a>.
%H A123693 E. Rowland, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/00029890.2022.2038004">Lucas' theorem modulo p^2</a>, American Mathematical Monthly, 129 (2022), no. 9, pp. 846-855.
%t A123693 Select[Prime[Range[1000000]], PowerMod[7, # - 1, #^2] == 1 &] (* _Robert Price_, May 17 2019 *)
%Y A123693 Cf. A001220, A014127, A123692, A128667, A128668, A090968, A039951, A128669.
